name: Jeff Duncan
content:
The Supreme Court just ruled, 9-0 unanimously, that non-citizens in the U.S. under a temporary status program cannot apply for green cards if they entered the country illegally.

Justice Elena Kagan wrote the opinion for the court and stated federal immigration law prohibits people who entered the country ILLEGALLY and now have Temporary Protected Status from seeking green cards to remain in the country permanently.

I am thankful to see the rule of law upheld and the judges' unanimous opinion. This is a defeat for the "America Last" provisions of the Biden administration and a victory for continuing President Trump's America First policies. It is also a defeat to open borders politicians like Senator Elizabeth Warren, Senator Ed Markey, Senator Mazie Hirono, Senator Richard Blumenthal, Senator Sheldon Whitehouse, Rep. Adriano Espaillat, and Rep. Debbie Wasserman Schultz, who urged the court to rule the other way.

name: Garret Graves
content:
PLEASE SHARE THIS POST:
Here is a link to a form for folks to fill out to share drainage photos with our office:

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSerYHbZsnK5JhiF0IJGqOEEkIMTxEyc5dnHOO2Wi9Sot0Srbw/viewform?fbclid=IwAR0ibkoE3kmAKmFcw53qQv5r6uYJSmurhe4KyRQ8gZ3w2Jzi18iZfgrVW1o

In an effort to help us identify the flooding and drainage problems for state officials managing these funds and some of the parishes working on this, please share this link and post.

*****************************************

Where are your drainage problems? We have been traveling around today and over the past several weeks talking with many of you about drainage and flooding problems. It is clear that there are problems all over south Louisiana. Some issues are related to leaves and litter getting into yards and streets -\-\ these block catch basins, ditches and canals (as seen in the pictures). In some cases, outfall pipes that were designed to drain our areas are too low in the canals -\-\ causing water to back-flow into our homes (as seen in the pictures). In other cases, it is canals, ditches, bayous and rivers that have not been properly maintained -\-\ filled with debris, trees, litter and sediment. We have secured a record $3,000,000,000 for the state and parishes to help address many of our flood/drainage problems. I'm not sure the funds are being put in the right places or executed with the urgency you deserve. The state has only spent a fraction of the $1.2 billion under a program we provided years ago -\-\ and almost none of this has been spent on actually fixing problems.
In an effort to help us identify the flooding and drainage problems for state officials managing these funds and some of the parishes working on this, post your pictures and the location of where water backs up.

name: Bill Johnson
content:
Today is the 77th anniversary of the D-Day landing‚Ä¶and, it‚Äôs befitting that we all stop and think for a moment about how God‚Äôs hand of divine providence ensured the success of that critical mission.

On June 6, 1944, some 175,000 allied and American troops waited to storm the beaches of Normandy, France to rid Europe of Nazi terror‚Ä¶among those were 57,000 Americans. I was at Normandy two years ago, and I overheard a veteran tell this story. He said, and I paraphrase‚Ä¶

When they were awakened that morning on June 6, it was pretty quiet on board the ships. They were busy getting their gear and weapons ready to go so that when it was their turn to get into the beach landing craft, they‚Äôd be ready. No one was talking, every man was deep in his thoughts. Then a superior came in and gave the mission orders‚Ä¶the pep talk. He said, ‚ÄúMen, your mission is to‚Ä¶take out two targets before you‚Äôre killed.‚Äù

Imagine hearing that, ‚Äútake out two targets before you‚Äôre killed!‚Äù That had to have been a very sobering pep talk. I can‚Äôt imagine what my reaction would have been upon hearing those words, but I hope it would have been the same reaction those men had. You see, in spite of knowing that there was a strong likelihood that many of them would be killed instantly, they all still got onto the beach landing craft.

I believe God showed up in the hearts and minds of those brave men that day‚Ä¶and, I suspect he reminded them of that emotional passage in the Bible. Because each and every one of those men, both those who died and those who miraculously survived, put everything on the line for not only their friends and families‚Ä¶but, for millions of people they did not even know.

John 15:13 ‚Äì ‚ÄúGreater love hath no man than this, that a man lay down his life for his friends.‚Äù

I‚Äôm grateful that God still touches the hearts of America‚Äôs young people and convinces them to put on the American military uniform and march off into harm‚Äôs way to protect and defend my freedom. Thank you to all those who served and are still serving today. God bless the United States of America.

Equal pay for equal work isn‚Äôt just an issue of fairness, it‚Äôs about economic security for working families. It is simply outrageous that in 2021, women are paid, on average, just 82 cents for every dollar paid to men. That wage gap widens for women of color.

For every dollar paid to white men, Black women are paid 63 cents.
Latina women are paid 55 cents.
Native American women are paid 63 cents.
Native Hawaiian and Pacific Islander women are paid 60 cents.

Pay inequality doesn‚Äôt just affect women‚Äîit impacts children, families, and our economy as a whole. The House already passed the #PaycheckFairness Act, and the American people overwhelmingly support fair pay policies. The Senate needs to pass this bill quickly‚Äîwith a straight up-or-down vote, no Republican filibuster‚Äîand get it to President Biden‚Äôs desk.

name: Bill Johnson
content:
Today marks 77 years since the D-Day invasion, the final push to free the world from Nazi tyranny. America, along with our allies, sent our most prized possession - our youth - onto French shores to defeat fascism and liberate a continent.

We‚Äôre making progress on getting the permanent plaque with the prayer President Franklin Roosevelt prayed with the nation on June 6, 1944. The World War II Memorial Prayer Act, that I authored along with Senator Portman, directs the Secretary of the Interior to install a plaque near the WWII Memorial with President Roosevelt‚Äôs words of the D-Day Prayer, ‚ÄúLet Our Hearts Be Stout.‚Äù Private funding has been secured, and the planning is almost complete. It's been a long process - the legislation was signed into law in 2014 - but we are nearing the finish line. FDR's powerful message should be seen by future generations that visit the memorial ‚Äì and thanks to our legislation, it soon will be.

name: Ralph Norman
content:
I want to highlight a few things in President Biden‚Äôs recent budget proposal, because it really speaks to where his priorities are.

First, the crazed spending. For context, the federal government spent $4.1 trillion in fiscal year 2019, before the pandemic. This year, with COVID almost in the rear-view, Biden is proposing‚Ä¶ get this‚Ä¶ $7.2 trillion in spending ‚Äì a 75% increase from 2019. And then $6 trillion in sustained annual spending in subsequent years. This is a liberal spending spree the likes of which we have never seen before.

Second, significantly higher taxes. Biden is proposing $55 trillion in ~new~ taxes over the next 10 years. That would be the highest sustained tax burden on the American people in the history of our nation. It would nearly double tax collection over the next decade. If you think most of that could be milked from corporations or top income earners, think again.

Third, more deficits. With our nation already $28 trillion in the hole, Biden‚Äôs looking to add another $14.7 trillion to that number over the next 10 years. That‚Äôs unconscionable.

Important side note: most of you know that I‚Äôve clashed with many in Congress (Republicans included) on our federal spending and debt. I will continue to oppose any budget that isn‚Äôt balanced and doesn‚Äôt have a plan for getting our debt under control.

Fourth, abortions. Biden‚Äôs proposal intentionally omits provisions of the Hyde Amendment, which prohibits taxpayer funding of abortions. Biden himself supported the Hyde Amendment as recently as 2019. Not anymore! It is jaw dropping that under Biden‚Äôs plan, taxpayer dollars could be used to end the life of an unborn child for convenience.

Fifth, our military, the one place where we shouldn‚Äôt skimp. Biden‚Äôs proposal for our armed forces does not keep up with inflation, which of course is rapidly rising on his watch. This means the equivalent funding for our military would be less if Biden gets his way.

What else? $0 for the border wall. Expansions of government run healthcare. Multiple billions for Green New Deal initiatives. The list is a mile long.

True to what Congressional Democrats seem to want, Biden‚Äôs budget proposal is a roadmap for higher spending, higher debt, and more individual dependence on the federal government. No thanks.

Seventy-seven years ago today, on June 6, 1944, 156,000 American, British and Canadian forces landed on five beaches along a 50-mile stretch of the heavily fortified coast of Normandy, France. The invasion was one of the largest amphibious military assaults in history and proved to be a critical turning point in World War II. More than 4,000 Allied soldiers, sailors, airmen, and coastguardsmen perished on the 24-hour period known as D-Day.

Two years ago, I participated in a bipartisan Congressional Delegation to commemorate the 75th Anniversary of D-Day. The experience was truly sobering and humbling. Seventy-seven years later, the sacrifice made on the beaches of Normandy must be remembered and revered. These brave souls demand that we earn the sacrifice they made by lifting up our freedom and our democracy and participating in our politics and government in a way that is nobler.

May we never forget the service and sacrifice of our "Greatest Generation."

name: Brian Babin
content:
In 2019, I traveled to France on a Congressional Delegation trip to pay tribute to the 75th anniversary of D-Day. Today, on the 77th anniversary, I‚Äôm remembering back on that most solemn experience. I‚Äôll never forget meeting with numerous veterans of D-Day, walking along the beaches of Normandy, peering inside German pillboxes, or visiting the graves of the nearly 10,000 soldiers who paid the ultimate price defending our liberty on June 6, 1944. It was an absolute honor to tread on such hallowed ground where so many heroes fell.

I remain incredibly proud to be an American, and am extremely grateful to those who have fought and died to ensure that our country, and its people, remain free.

name: Mike Lee
content:
If we are to compete with China and maintain our leadership in technology, we ought to do what America has always done best.

Instead of chilling innovation and competition, we ought to decentralize power and champion trust in the private sector.
We ought to decrease regulation, not invest in regulatory bodies.
We ought to simplify and cut taxes, not off-shore our jobs.
We ought to use our critical minerals, not let them languish.
We ought to partner with our allies, not restrict fair trade.
We ought to harvest timber, not organs.
We ought to defend families, not diminish them.
We ought to encourage entrepreneurship, not crony capitalism.
We ought to strengthen markets, not government.

I urge my colleagues to reject the Endless Frontier Act.

name: Bill Johnson
content: Lancaster, Ohio native General William Sherman is this week‚Äôs famous Ohioan. His military career began at West Point at age 16, where he rose through the ranks, eventually replacing Ulysses S. Grant as the Union Commander during the Civil War. A few years later, he was made the Commanding General of the Army, a post he held for over 10 years under four presidents. His aggressive military strategies have been studied throughout the years, and inspired many famous military minds, including General George S. Patton. He played pivotal roles in holding America together during the Civil War and rebuilding America during post-Civil War reconstruction.

name: Doug LaMalfa
content: I led a Western Caucus Foundation panel discussion on how state, local, and federal governments can work together to better tackle wildfires. I spoke on the need for the forest service to improve contracting to ensure local fire assets, bulldozers, water trucks and heavy equipment that are located closest to the fire can be used to put out fires quickly before they become large catastrophic fires. We also discussed the shortages of state hand crews because of changes by Governor Newsom that have reduced participation in prison hand crews by over 65%. Now more than ever, pre-contracted bulldozers and other fire equipment will be needed to make up for the lack of personnel available to fight fires. I‚Äôm thankful to Young America‚Äôs Foundation President Scott Walker and California Farm Bureau President Jamie Johanssen for facilitating the panel and for their support.

The VA estimates that nearly 20 veterans take their own lives each day in the US, oftentimes due to the invisible wounds known as Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder. This PTSD Awareness Month, it's important to honor and remember all those who have lost their lives to this terrible affliction, but we must also work to spread the word about treatment options for those suffering from PTSD. The PFC Joseph P. Dwyer Veteran Peer Support Program, which I created while serving in the New York State Senate, helps veterans overcome PTSD and successfully transition to post-service life by creating a safe, confidential and educational network for veterans to support each other and share common experiences. I'm so grateful for the many amazing veterans advocates across New York who have helped save countless veteran lives due to their efforts to make the Dwyer Program a huge success in our state. name: Doris O. Matsui
content:
The ‚ÄúGo For Broke‚Äù US Postal Service stamp honors the bravery of the all-Japanese American 442nd Regimental Combat team, one of the most distinguished American fighting units of World War II, whose motto was ‚Äúgo for broke.‚Äù

This stamp also educates Americans about the forced relocation and incarceration of over 120,000 Japanese Americans through Executive Order 9066, which is now considered one of the most atrocious violations of American civil rights in the 20th century. They are reminded of our story ‚Äî one of tragedy and perseverance.

It's an important reminder that our story continues. Decades after World War II, Asian Americans in our country continue to face discrimination and face injustice due to their heritage. But this hate will not stop us from lifting up our stories and fighting for a more just future. The Japanese American experience is a vital piece to this puzzle. It is a story that cannot afford to be lost in time.

It was an honor to share in the celebration of this stamp on Saturday.

name: Brian Babin
content:
Seventy-seven years ago, the ‚ÄúDay of Days‚Äù commenced as the U.S. launched the largest amphibious invasion in the history of warfare, preceded by an airborne assault, along the beaches of Normandy, France. As Operation Neptune unfolded, thousands of American and Allied troops courageously took to the beaches to fight ‚Äì willing to sacrifice all ‚Äì for freedom. Only those who experienced it can truly fathom the bravery displayed by so many on D-Day as Allied forces victoriously took Normandy and turned the tide of the war. Eventually, this led to the liberation of Europe and the defeat of Nazi Germany.

Today, join me in remembering and thanking the heroes who stormed the beaches, piloted the planes, parachuted behind enemy lines, operated the thousands of ships, and fought valiantly to preserve the freedoms we cherish every single day. The weight of this sacrifice is as heavy today as it was in 1944. While the liberation of Europe came at a high price, it is a price America has always been willing to pay in the protection of freedom.

‚ÄúThe eyes of the world are upon you. The hopes and prayers of liberty-loving people everywhere march with you.‚Äù ‚Äì General Dwight D. Eisenhower, 1944

name: J. Hill
content:
Today, 77 years ago, the Allied Forces forces of the United States, Britian, Canada, and France gained a victory over Axis powers marking the turning point in World War II.

Then-General Dwight D. Eisenhower, Supreme Allied Commander, encouraged his troops on June 6, 1944, saying, "Your task will not be an easy one. Your enemy is well-trained, well equipped and battle-hardened. He will fight savagely‚Ä¶. I have full confidence in your courage, devotion to duty and skill in battle. We will accept nothing less than full Victory!"

General Eisenhower's confidence in his troops, as well as the wherewithal of Allied troops, helped protect the freedoms we enjoy today at home and across the entire continent of Europe. Allied forces went on to accept Germany‚Äôs unconditional surrender not twelve months later on May 8, 1945.

name: Steve Chabot
content: 77 years ago today, the D-Day invasion began, as more than 150,000 Allied troops stormed the beaches of Normandy. It's difficult to overstate just how critical the Normandy invasion was not only to our success in World War II, but also to the future of democracy and freedom around the globe. As President Franklin D. Roosevelt said of the Allied soldiers when announcing the invasion to the American people: "They fight not for the lust of conquest. They fight to end conquest. They fight to liberate." And liberate they did. A little less than a year later, Nazi Germany was defeated, and the War in Europe was over. We owe a tremendous amount of gratitude to the men and women of the greatest generation for the sacrifices they made, both at home and abroad, to keep us free and protect us from tyranny. God bless each of you, and God bless America!

name: Lisa Murkowski
content: While in Fairbanks last week I stopped by the Riverboat Discovery for a conversation with owners, Ryan and John Binkley. Like many Alaskan businesses that rely on tourism, the Riverboat Discovery saw drastic losses in revenue due to an almost non-existent 2020 tourism season. But this year they are slowly starting to welcome back visitors ‚Äì projecting about 10% of a normal year. The Riverboat Discovery isn‚Äôt operating at full capacity yet and their staff numbers are down, but Ryan shared something that really resonated with me. Ryan mentioned that because of my legislation ‚Äî the Alaska Tourism Restoration Act ‚Äî boats are getting back in the water and that even at a fraction of what is normal for a year, it is a signal of hope to all Alaskans. It is a great sign that stronger days are ahead.

name: Mark Takano
content:
"When I first came out as transgender, I had a lot of fear to overcome. Even though I had the support of my parents, I was worried that I would be held back by discrimination, especially in the workplace.

I spent my first summer after coming out back home in a conservative suburb of Ohio, and I immediately went back in the closet for work. The whole time was miserable. I was living a lie worried that I might lose my job. At the summer‚Äôs end, I had resolved to never hide who I was regardless of the risk, because nobody should have to live a lie.

I spent the next five years working, volunteering for causes, and doing direct action for my community. And now I‚Äôm making a difference as a leader. Along with my Co-Lead, I lead a 20 person team that schedules vaccine appointments in Moreno Valley, Riverside and Jurupa Valley as part of Healthy Future California. We have already scheduled nearly 2,000 vaccine appointments.

I bear a lot of responsibility on my shoulders. In addition to helping the state fight back against Covid-19, I have a duty as a transgender employer. Few Americans work alongside other transgender employees, and almost nobody has worked under one. My greatest wish is that the work that I am doing will help other LGBT+ Americans to be recognized for the meaningful contributions they make, so that may rise up and become leaders as well."

Bridget, Riverside
#HumansofCA41

name: Alan S. Lowenthal
content:
The slaves of Galveston, Texas, had to wait more than two years after President Lincoln‚Äôs Emancipation Proclamation and two months after the end of the Civil War to receive word that they were now free. As President Obama said in one of his June 19th proclamations observing Juneteenth, ‚ÄúToday, we commemorate the anniversary of that delayed but welcome news.‚Äù

For 155 years, Juneteenth has been both a celebration of freedom and heritage and also a solemn reminder of the legacies of slavery and racism which scar our country.

On Saturday, June 19th, Downtown Long Beach will be hosting a large Juneteenth celebration from 11am to 4pm. The celebration will be filled with music, poetry, dancing, and community. The event will also bring together our community after downtown has struggled due to COVID-19 restrictions.

To find out more please visit http://www.LBJuneteenth.com.

LBJUNETEENTH.COM
Long Beach Juneteenth Celebration | June 19th

name: Tom Cole
content:
At the end of last month, President Joe Biden sent a $6 trillion budget request to Congress for fiscal year 2022. Proposing the highest spending levels since World War II, the price tag alone is utterly outrageous and unrealistic. And while Congress holds the purse strings and is ultimately responsible for providing the annual funding for the federal government, the president‚Äôs budget request reveals his radical priorities and proves his total disregard for fiscal responsibility.

First, instead of focusing on urgent priorities for all Americans, President Biden‚Äôs budget request elevates controversial policies over pressing needs like strengthening our national defense and bolstering tools to address and manage the crisis at our southern border. In fact, his budget calls for billions of dollars to fund progressive policies like Medicare for All, the Green New Deal and those outlined in his so-called American Jobs Plan and American Families Plan while recommending an effective cut in funding for our military. With China and Russia growing their militaries by the day, such a move is deeply misguided.

Beyond short changing our defense and spending big on progressive policies, President Biden expects the American people to foot the bill. His budget proposes a $55 trillion tax increase on American individuals and businesses over the next decade. Moreover, the president endorsed raising the corporate income tax rate and other taxes targeting individuals, small businesses and our independent energy industries.

Despite promises made on the campaign trail not to raise taxes on those with low and middle income, the president‚Äôs budget would also allow existing tax cuts to expire, which would immediately increase the tax burden on hardworking Americans. As individuals, families and small businesses continue to recover from the coronavirus pandemic, such levels of unprecedented spending and taxation would only lead to inflation, slowed economic growth and the highest national debt level in American history.

Finally, most egregious in the president‚Äôs budget request is the recommended removal of the Hyde Amendment, which protects life and prevents federal taxpayer-funded abortions. Since it was first enacted in 1976, it is estimated that this provision has saved more than two million lives while protecting the conscience rights of the great majority of Americans who are opposed to publicly funded abortions for religious, moral or fiscal reasons.

Even when President Biden was serving in the United States Senate, he then expressed his support for inclusion of Hyde Amendment in appropriations bills and showed support for the provision as recently as just two years ago while campaigning for president. Moreover, it has been supported by lawmakers and signed into law by presidents of both parties every year as part of appropriations bills. To abandon support of it now reveals that he is actually the most pro-abortion president in history.

Fortunately, for the American people, Democrats in Congress do not have the majorities capable of passing this level of expansive programs on their own. In the days and weeks ahead, it is my hope that members on both sides of the aisle and in both chambers can negotiate spending that is reasonable and will not lead to financial disaster. In fact, projections included in the president‚Äôs budget reveal that enacting such spending would add $17 trillion to the national debt by 2031.

Alarmingly, our country‚Äôs enormous and growing debt already exceeds an astounding $28 trillion. The last thing America needs is President Biden‚Äôs proposed tax-and-spend monstrosity. To be clear, navigating the coronavirus pandemic response and recovery greatly strained communities across the nation, which led to five bipartisan and massive packages to support emergency efforts. But the situation has changed dramatically since then. Communities are reopening. People are getting vaccinated. Life is starting to return to a relative normal. Rather than proposing trillions in spending on non-pandemic related programs and initiatives, the president should be focused on fostering the nation‚Äôs economic recovery.

Sadly, Americans are already suffering through the highest inflation on record in 13 years. With this budget request, the Biden Administration has demonstrated yet again that its solution for everything is to tax, spend and then spend some more. Such misguided and unnecessary expansion of government is not sustainable for America‚Äôs future. Moreover, we simply cannot afford it.

name: John Boozman
content:
Arkansas, like other states, is rebounding from the pandemic in a stronger position than we might have expected around this time last year.

Last month the governor announced Arkansas will opt out of the federal supplemental unemployment assistance program. The move, which becomes effective later in June, is designed to encourage more Arkansans to rejoin the workforce now that we are getting back to normal through widespread access to the COVID-19 vaccines and better understanding of the transmission of the virus.

I applaud the governor for taking this step to help spur economic recovery. As I talk with business owners around the state, it is clear that labor is in short supply. Common sense tells us that an enhanced $300 per week federal unemployment supplement, on top of existing benefits, is contributing to this shortage of workers.

Employers are desperate for more help. They're telling anyone who will listen about how this crisis is affecting their ability to stay open and provide the services their customers rely on.

Read the full version of my latest column at the link below or on my website.

https://www.thesuntimes.com/opinion/help-wanted-getting-arkansans-back-to-work/article_a1a95c9f-3688-5415-84ce-32f52b05558f.html

THESUNTIMES.COM

name: Lisa Murkowski
content: While in Fairbanks I met with a mix of stakeholders, including parents and childcare providers, to talk through some of the challenges they continue to face. I heard from parents who were forced to quit their job to provide care for their kids and from a mother who had been on a childcare waitlist for around three years. I also heard from agency leaders who described the hardships of keeping their doors open and adequately staffed, particularly during the pandemic. Parents and childcare providers alike have been getting creative to try to fill the gaps in care but significant challenges remain. I look forward to continuing my efforts alongside them to ensure that parents and families have access to quality, affordable care for their children.

name: Robert E. Latta
content:
Our nation was once again hit with a cyberattack that has caused an industry to stop production. JBS is the world‚Äôs largest international meat processor. The ransomware attack has caused the company to take their systems offline and stop work in both North America and Australia. This cyberattack could significantly impact the US‚Äôs beef-processing capacity resulting in meat shortages across the country.

This attack is another example of how our nation is unprepared to handle cyberattacks. The public and private sectors must stay vigilant and guard themselves against attacks. While the previous high-profile attack was on Colonial Pipeline, this just shows that every industry and sector need to take steps to protect themselves and their data.

These hackers are constantly probing our institutions for vulnerabilities, including our companies, utilities, governments, and financial systems. President Biden needs to stand up to these Russian hackers and make it clear that the United States does not tolerate threats to our security and well-being.

name: James P. McGovern
content:
Yesterday at The Food Bank of Western Mass. I was thrilled to welcome Joel Berg of Hunger Free America as part of a national tour to help re-focus attention on America‚Äôs hunger crisis.

Throughout the pandemic, Joel and I have shared a common goal of raising awareness of the fact that food insecurity in the United States remains critically high and we‚Äôve stressed the need to provide the American people with long-term solutions.

We visited The Food Bank farm in Hadley, which provides an innovative approach to addressing food insecurity in Western Massachusetts.

The local impact of the work being done in Hadley should be highlighted and modeled on a national level. And I plan to do just that.

Since the beginning of the 117th Congress, as Chairman of the Rules Committee, I‚Äôve begun a series of nationwide anti-hunger hearings, roundtables, meetings, press conferences, and visits to uplift a diverse chorus of voices, so that when the Biden administration is ready to hold a hunger conference, they can hit the ground running with ideas and feedback readily available to help shape the dialogue.

While I appreciate Joel‚Äôs visit and attention to the Food Bank‚Äôs work, in a perfect world, his job wouldn‚Äôt even exist because there there‚Äôs simply no excuse for hunger is the wealthiest nation in world history.

This farm is the kind of program that we want to uplift as a path towards a hunger free America!

From The Wall Street Journal editorial board on partisan gerrymandering in Illinois:

‚ÄúIllinois Democrats hold a statehouse supermajority, every statewide office and a state Supreme Court majority. That sounds like a monopoly on power. name: Doug Lamborn
content:
June 6th 2021 marks the 77th anniversary of D-Day and the Battle of Normandy.

Today we remember and honor the brave and we commemorate our heroes who came from far and wide to restore freedom to Europe and across the world.

The National WWII Museum posted a video to playlist Voices of The Greatest Generation.
June 6, 2016 at 7:25 AM ¬∑

To all who landed on Omaha Beach on June 6, 1944, it will be remembered as "Bloody Omaha" to them.

#OnThisDay in 1944, the Allies suffered approximately 12,000 casualties. The men that survived this bloody first 24 hours on the beaches of Normandy would embark upon a campaign to liberate northern France and drive towards Paris. But victory over Nazism was a far distant goal as the day ended on June 6, 1944. Berlin remained nearly 700 miles distant from Normandy. Much hard fighting remained for the Allied forces.

Visitors to the Museum can follow in the footsteps of these American troops as they make their way into Germany in our exhibit Road to Berlin: http://bit.ly/1SLGsrZ #DDay72 #DDay

name: Dan Sullivan
content:
This weekend, I led the first congressional visit to the Republic of Korea since the onset of the pandemic with my colleagues Senators Tammy Duckworth and Chris Coons, sending a resounding, bipartisan message of mutual support between our two countries. The U.S.-Korean alliance dates back to the Korean War when our soldiers fought side by side to defeat North Korean communist aggression. I respect so much how, even to this day, the Republic of Korea‚Äôs elected leaders and citizens continue to express their appreciation for the sacrifice of tens of thousands of American servicemen who have helped make the country free and prosperous.

I want to thank Prime Minister Kim Boo-Kyum, Defense Minister Suh Wook, Foreign Minister Chung Eui-yong, and Trade Minister Moon Sung-wook for warmly welcoming us and reaffirming the U.S.-R.O.K. alliance, which forms the linchpin of peace, security, and prosperity in the Indo-Pacific region.

name: Warren Davidson
content:
Serving as the Ranking Member of the FinTech Task Force is an incredible honor. This podcast highlights some of the changes in market infrastructure that have made America's capital markets more accessible for more Americans. Some of the topics in the House Financial Services Committee aren't inherently political, but they're incredibly important. Inflation has a pernicious effect, often benefiting those with investments before it flows through the economy driving up consumer prices - and harming everyone. When to invest, how to invest, and what to invest in are complex questions - often answered by professional investment managers. But, as information has become more accessible, more people have chosen to make their own decisions with at least a portion of their savings. I hope you enjoy this bit of history...

WSJ.COM
To The Moon, Part 3: A People's History of Investing - The Journal. - WSJ Podcasts

name: Thomas R. Suozzi
content:
Busy day in the District!

Four good meetings.

1) I went to the Northport VA to meet with Col. Matthew Luzzatto, New York District Commander and District Engineer of the US Army Corps of Engineers to discuss the commencement of the demolition of Buildings 1 & 2.

2) I met with US Coast Guard Captain Eva Van Camp, Commander of Sector Long Island Sound at Station Eatons Neck to talk about the Coast Guard‚Äôs important work in our area.

3) Col. Luzzatto and I then met with the Mayor of Northport Village to discuss dredging of Northport Harbor.

4) The last stop of the day was with baymen in Bayville where Col. Luzzatto and I discussed the negative impacts of hydraulic shellfish dredging on the surrounding seabed with local baymen.

Look for more photos and details in the coming days.

name: James M. Inhofe
content:
Since its creation, the MKARNS has promoted freight mobility, expanded agricultural exports and enabled the cost effective movement of iron, steel, and other products‚Äîempowering economic development and job growth across Oklahoma. This vital economic engine and freight corridor was the largest Army Corps of Engineers civil works project undertaken at the time of its construction and is most deserving of celebration. It has been a top priority of mine to work with a vast array of stakeholders, including the five public ports, 50 private terminals and over 90 industries that use the MKARNS, to ensure our inland waterway remains a key navigation channel. As we look to the next 50 years of operations, we will work together to modernize and deepen our marine highway so it can continue to anchor economic growth and prosperity for the entire region over the next 50 years.

name: Lisa Murkowski
content:
The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service recently published proposed marine mammal Incidental Take Regulations (ITR), commonly known as the Polar Bear ITRs, in the Federal Register for public comment. These proposed regulations come after I repeatedly pressed Department of the Interior officials and nominees on the urgency and importance of these regulations being updated and issued as the last ITRs expires in August of this year. These regulations, if adopted, would make it possible for oil and gas development to continue on the North Slope for the foreseeable future. I thank the Fish and Wildlife Service, and in particular their career staff and technical experts, for their dedication to working through this issue. I look forward to ensuring that a robust public comment period is carried out, and that the August deadline to adopt the new regulations is met.

MURKOWSKI.SENATE.GOV
Murkowski Welcomes Fish & Wildlife Service Polar Bear Proposed ITRs | U.S. Senator Lisa Murkowski of Alaska

name: Don Young
content:
NEW

I‚Äôm happy to announce that THREE of the Member Directed Projects I requested and advocated for have been APPROVED by the Transportation and Infrastructure Committee!

They are:

‚úÖ $8.7 million for the reconstruction of Cowles Street In Fairbanks.

‚úÖ $6.4 million to replace Bridge 114.3, used by the Alaska Railroad, in Anchorage.

‚úÖ $5.6 million for Phase 2 of the Seldon Road Extension in Wasilla.

For too long, my colleagues and I have been unable to directly request funding for specific projects in our districts. This decade-long ban on 'earmarks' served only to shift Congress' rightful power to appropriate money to the Executive Branch, while denying needed funds to local entities. This Congress, through the Member Directed Projects program, we have begun to take incremental steps toward fully restoring the Article I powers of Congress.

The Alaska Railroad is a critical part of our economy. I am pleased that the Committee has approved replacing the structurally obsolete bridge at the Railroad's Anchorage yard. In Wasilla, I have secured approval for the Seldon Road Phase 2 extension, which would increase access to schools, and emergency services such as firefighters and paramedics. Finally, the Cowles Street reconstruction project's approval would improve connections between communities and bolster Cowles Street, which provides 61% of the community's total annual ridership.

Discussions surrounding federal investments in infrastructure will continue, and Alaskans can count on me to keep standing up for our state and its unique transportation needs. Although an improvement over the status quo, this process was flawed in that Members were evenly allotted a set amount of funding without taking into account the size or makeup of their districts.

Unfortunately, this program favored large population states at the expense geographically expansive states like Alaska, which generally have higher project costs.

It is my great hope that the Member Directed Projects program proves successful and is updated appropriately so that we as a Congress can better support our constituents using the power of the purse.

Read more ‚¨á

name: Mike Quigley
content:
Earlier this year, I submitted five projects to the House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure for possible inclusion in the next surface transportation authorization legislation. The projects would include improvements to local roads, trails and CTA stops.

Today, I was thrilled to learn that all five projects were approved by the Committee to be included in their proposed legislation.

This is just one step in the process - we still have to pass the bill and get it signed into law - but I'm excited to have made it to this stage.

Here are some details about each of the five projects:

If this legislation is signed into law:

‚úÖ CTA's Blue Line Irving Park stop would receive funding for badly needed improvements, including two new station houses equipped with customer assistance kiosks.

‚úÖ Pace‚Äôs bus service on Cermark Road could implement transit signal priority enabling buses to communicate with traffic signals to help make public transit on this route safe, efficient, and reliable.

‚úÖ The 606 multi-use trail would be extended from Ashland Avenue to Elston Avenue, connecting the east and west sides of the Kennedy Expressway and UP Railroad tracks.

‚úÖ The Illinois Department of Transportation would be able to resurface and replace curb ramps on Ill 64 North Ave to make them compliant with the Americans with Disabilities Act.

‚úÖ Last, but far from least, Belmont Avenue could also be resurfaced and curb ramps could be replaced from 25th Ave to W of Elm St, Franklin Park.

These are small local projects that would have a major impact on our communities because we all benefit from reliable, accessible transportation and infrastructure.

That‚Äôs why I was so proud to support these local projects and why I won‚Äôt be done fighting for them until this legislation becomes law and our community‚Äôs projects are funded.

Want to learn more about the projects I submitted and am fighting for? Click below:

name: U.S. Helsinki Commission
content:
In a recent article in The Ukrainian Weekly, longtime Helsinki Commission policy advisor Orest Deychakiwsky reflected on his decades of commission service, as well as the accomplishments of the commission in its early decades:

‚ÄúThe Helsinki Commission encouraged our own government to make human rights a centerpiece of foreign policy in general and, more narrowly, in our relations with the Soviet Union and the other communist countries of Eastern Europe. For instance, we pushed the State Department to become more assertive in discussing specific instances of rights violations, including ‚Äònaming names‚Äô of individual cases of political prisoners. After a while, some of our more cautious European allies began to follow suit.‚Äù

#HelsinkiComm45

The United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO) will conduct a virtual National Summer Teacher Institute (NSTI) on Innovation, STEM, and Intellectual Property ‚Äì July 19-23, 2021.

NSTI combines experiential training tools and practices with project and problem-based learning to support K12 teachers in increasing their knowledge of inventing and ‚Äúmaking‚Äù while learning about the creation and protection of IP.

Participants work in groups on invention projects of their choice and hear from subject matter experts and instructors on IP from the USPTO, scientists, engineers, entrepreneurs, and STEM professionals from federal government agencies and non-profit organizations.

Deadline to submit your application is Tuesday, June 15, 2021.
